Australia strongly opposes Japan's plans to expand whaling in Antarctic waters, fearing damage to their perception of Japan.
Despite this, they won't board Japanese ships to avoid piracy accusations.
Environment Minister Ian Campbell warns of Japan's reputation risk if they persist.
Australia vows to prevent commercial and scientific whaling, urging Japan to reconsider.
Prime Minister John Howard diplomatically urges Japan to halt whale hunting.
Legal battles against Japanese whaling have faced setbacks, with Australia's jurisdictional claims being challenged.
Animal rights groups plan appeals to stop the slaughter of whales, while New Zealand considers legal action against Japan's plans.
